Java Support multithreading by default no need to install any library. Java ke andar Thread class aur Runnable interface hai jo multithreading support karte hai. Thread class ke andar run() method hota hai jisme thread ka kaam define hota hai. Runnable interface ke andar bhi run() method hota hai, aur isko implement karke thread create kiya ja sakta hai.

JVM multithreading ko possible banata hai in tarikon se :
Thread creation aur mapping: Jab tu Java mein new Thread() banata hai aur .start() call karta hai, JVM internally us Java thread ko ek native OS thread se map karta hai.
Memory management per thread: JVM har thread ko apna separate JVM Stack deta hai. Lekin Heap saare threads ke beech shared hota hai same process (JVM instance) ke andar.
Thread Scheduler: JVM khud threads ko schedule nahi karta — ye kaam underlying OS ka thread scheduler karta hai. JVM sirf request karta hai ki thread ko ready state mein daal do, actual CPU time allotment OS decide karta hai (priority, time-slicing, etc. ke basis pe). Isliye Java mein thread priority sirf ek "hint" hoti hai, guarantee nahi.
Garbage Collection aur Thread Safety: JVM ke garbage collector ko bhi multithreading ka dhyan rakhna padta hai. Agar multiple threads ek hi object ko access kar rahe hai, to JVM ensure karta hai ki GC thread-safe ho, taaki memory corruption na ho.
Thread lifeCycle management: JVM thread lifecycle ko manage karta hai (New, Runnable, Running, Waiting, Timed Waiting, Terminated). JVM internally OS ke thread states ke saath map karta hai.

