Thread Lifecycle in Java
Java mein thread apne life mein 6 states se guzarta hai (Thread.State enum define karta hai ye states):
1. NEW
Thread object create ho gaya hai (new Thread()), lekin abhi .start() call nahi hua. Is state mein thread ka koi actual OS-level thread nahi bana hota, sirf Java object exist karta hai.
2. RUNNABLE
.start() call hote hi thread NEW se RUNNABLE state mein aata hai. Is state ka matlab hai thread execute hone ke liye ready hai ya actually execute ho raha hai — Java in dono situations (ready + running) ko ek hi RUNNABLE state maanta hai (kyunki actual CPU allotment OS scheduler decide karta hai, JVM ke control mein nahi hai).But acutal me running state bol dete hai
3. BLOCKED
Thread kisi monitor lock (synchronized block/method) ka wait kar raha hai jo kisi doosre thread ke paas hai. Jab tak wo lock free nahi hota, thread BLOCKED state mein rehta hai. Lock milte hi RUNNABLE mein wapas chala jata hai.
4. WAITING
Thread indefinitely wait kar raha hai kisi doosre thread ke specific action ka (jaise notify() call hona, ya thread ka finish hona). Ye state khud se timeout nahi hota — koi external signal chahiye wapas RUNNABLE hone ke liye.
Ye state milta hai methods jaise: wait() (bina timeout), join() (bina timeout), park() se.
5. TIMED_WAITING
Same as WAITING, but ek fixed time ke liye wait karta hai — time khatam hote hi khud RUNNABLE mein wapas aa jata hai (chahe signal mile ya na mile).
Ye state milta hai methods jaise: sleep(time), wait(timeout), join(timeout) se.
6. TERMINATED (Dead)
Thread ka run() method complete ho gaya (normally ya kisi exception ki wajah se). Ek baar TERMINATED hone ke baad thread dobara start nahi ho sakta — dobara .start() call karne pe IllegalThreadStateException aata hai.

